04305nmm a2200601Ia 9780801465727DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979622590  a97808014657277 a10.7591/97808014657272doi  a(DE-B1597)478323  a(OCoLC)961513327  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN2287.T164bE73 201604a791.0922231 aErdman, Andrew L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueen of Vaudeville :bThe Story of Eva Tanguay /cAndrew L. Erdman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b19 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn her day, Eva Tanguay (1879–1947) was one of the most famous women in America. Widely known as the "I Don’t Care Girl"—named after a song she popularized and her independent, even brazen persona—Tanguay established herself as a vaudeville and musical comedy star in 1901 with the New York City premiere of the show My Lady—and never looked back. Tanguay was, at the height of a long career that stretched until the early 1930s, a trend-setting performer who embodied the emerging ideal of the bold and sexual female entertainer. Whether suggestively singing songs with titles like "It’s All Been Done Before But Not the Way I Do It" and "Go As Far As You Like" or wearing a daring dress made of pennies, she was a precursor to subsequent generations of performers, from Mae West to Madonna and Lady Gaga, who have been both idolized and condemned for simultaneously displaying and playing with blatant displays of female sexuality.In Queen of Vaudeville, Andrew L. Erdman tells Eva Tanguay’s remarkable life story with verve. Born into the family of a country doctor in rural Quebec and raised in a New England mill town, Tanguay found a home on the vaudeville stage. Erdman follows the course of her life as she amasses fame and wealth, marries (and divorces) twice, engages in affairs closely followed in the press, declares herself a Christian Scientist, becomes one of the first celebrities to get plastic surgery, loses her fortune following the Wall Street Crash of 1929, and receives her last notice, an obituary in Variety. The arc of Tanguay’s career follows the history of American popular culture in the first half of the twentieth century. Tanguay’s appeal, so dependent on her physical presence and personal charisma, did not come across in the new media of radio and motion pictures. With nineteen rare or previously unpublished images, Queen of Vaudeville is a dynamic portrait of a dazzling and unjustly forgotten show business star.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aVaudevillexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aVaudevillezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen entertainersxBiographyxUnited States. 0aWomen entertainerszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aArt History. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146572740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801465727423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801465727/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles